{
  "texts": [
    "In the times long before hypertext and digital devices, text took the form of markings on paper (if not parchment, silk, tablets, or another usable surface), grouped into distinct strings of characters (or other symbols, depending on a particular writing system adopted).",
    "A properly designed work of reference should provide users with a way to navigate to the pertinent section.",
    "For this, early lexicography adopted a signposting system using distinct strings of characters, most typically words for word-based languages.",
    "They were arranged in a conventional order, that is alphabetical for languages having an alphabet.",
    "Non-alphabetic languages resorted to other ordering principles."
  ]
}